08167nam a22012135i 9780823289783DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232897837 a10.1515/97808232897832doi  a(DE-B1597)574291  a(OCoLC)1227951035  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aMUS0500002bisacsh04a780.9222300aArvo Pärt :bSounding the Sacred /ced. by Robert Saler, Jeffers Engelhardt, Peter C. Bouteneff. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b2 b/w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tI. INTRODUCTION -- t1. Arvo Pärt and the Art of Embodiment -- t2. The Sound-and Hearing-of Arvo Pärt -- tII. HISTORY AND CONTEXT -- t3. Sounding Structure, Structured Sound -- t4. Colorful Dreams: Exploring Pärt's Soviet Film Music -- t5. Arvo Pärt's Tintinnabuli and the 1970s Soviet Underground -- tIII. PERFORMANCE -- t6. The Pärt Sound -- t7. The Rest Is Silence -- tIV. MATERIALITY AND PHENOMENOLOGY -- t8. Vibrating, and Silent: Listening to the Material Acoustics of Tintinnabulation -- t9. Medieval Pärt -- t10. The Piano and the Performing Body in the Music of Arvo Pärt: Phenomenological Perspectives -- tV. THEOLOGY -- t11. Presence, Absence, and the Ambiguities of Ambiance: Theological Discourse and the Move to Sound in Pärt Studies -- t12. The Materiality of Sound and the Theology of the Incarnation in the Music of Arvo Pärt -- t13. Christian Liturgical Chant and the Musical Reorientation of Arvo Pärt -- t14. In the Beginning There Was Sound: Hearing, Tintinnabuli, and Musical Meaning in Sufi -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Terms -- tIndex of Persons -- tWorks by Other Composers -- tWorks by Arvo Pärt0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aScholarly writing on the music of Arvo Pärt is situated primarily in the fields of musicology, cultural and media studies, and, more recently, in terms of theology/spirituality. Arvo Pärt: Sounding the Sacred focuses on the representational dimensions of Pärt's music (including the trope of silence), writing and listening past the fact that its storied effects and affects are carried first and foremost as vibrations through air, impressing themselves on the human body. In response, this ambitiously interdisciplinary volume asks: What of sound and materiality as embodiments of the sacred, as historically specific artifacts, and as elements of creation deeply linked to the human sensorium in Pärt studies? In taking up these questions, the book "de-Platonizes" Pärt studies by demystifying the notion of a single "Pärt sound." It offers innovative, critical analyses of the historical contexts of Pärt's experimentation, medievalism, and diverse creative work; it re-sounds the acoustic, theological, and representational grounds of silence in Pärt's music; it listens with critical openness to the intersections of theology, sacred texts, and spirituality in Pärt's music; and it positions sensing, performing bodies at the center of musical experience. Building on the conventional score-, biography-, and media-based approaches, this volume reframes Pärt studies around the materiality of sound, its sacredness, and its embodied resonances within secular spaces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMusicxReligious aspects. 0aSoundxReligious aspects. 7aMUSIC / Individual Composer & Musician.2bisacsh  aArvo Pärt.  aEstonia.  aOrthodox Christianity.  aSoviet music.  aembodiment.  amateriality.  amusic studies.  areligious studies.  asound studies.  atheology.1 aAlbin, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlbin, Andrew.1 